library(dplyr)

library(ggplot2)
room_data <- read.csv("../data/fixed_room_data.csv")
room_order <- read.csv("../data/unique_room_list_double_hundo_fixed_with_index.csv", header = FALSE, col.names = c('Number','Room'))

Lets start with a data frame were we calculate the number of times each room is entered and each time the run ends on the run.

my_count <- room_data %>%
  group_by(Room) %>%
  summarise(times_killed_run = sum(is.na(Duration)), times_entered = length (Duration) )

So heres a bit of magic you need to make sure stuff is displayed in right order. Ill need to fix this later thougn because the order might not be 100% correct.

rooms_ordered <- merge(my_count, room_order, by= "Room")
rooms_ordered$Room <- 
  reorder(rooms_ordered$Room, rooms_ordered$Number)

And lets make a first go at ploting this stuff up.

ggplot(rooms_ordered, aes(y=times_entered,x=Room, f)) + 
  geom_point(color = 'darkred')

The first thing to fix here is that there are WAY too many x-labels.

ggplot(rooms_ordered, aes(y=times_entered,x=Room, f)) + 
  geom_point(color = 'darkred') +
  scale_x_discrete(name="Room Number",limits=c('1OH81
', '3DG81', '2OD71'))

Ok so that didnt really work like I thought it might, it filters points. Now lets try soemthing else

ggplot(rooms_ordered, aes(y=times_entered,x=Room, f)) + 
  geom_point(color = 'darkred') +
  theme(axis.text.x = element_blank(),axis.ticks = element_blank())

Ok that gets rid of the Room numbers which I suppose is better. Lets try with our truncated list again

ggplot(rooms_ordered, aes(y=times_entered,x=Room, f)) +

Lets do a quick test with ggplot, I want to know if it is possible to shorten my room rectangles.

add_rects <- function() {
  annotate("rect",xmin = '3DG81', xmax = '3DH41', ymin = -Inf, ymax = Inf, alpha = 0.3, fill = 'blue' )
#  geom_rect(aes(y=times_killed_run/times_entered, x = Room, xmin = '3DG81', xmax = '3DH41', ymin = -Inf, ymax = Inf), data = rooms_ordered, alpha=0.3 , fill = 'green')
}
rooms_to_display = c('1OH81', '2OD71', '3OF61', '4OH41', '5OL11', 
                     '6OM41', '7OC51', '8OC31', '9ON71')
ggplot(rooms_ordered, aes(y=times_killed_run/times_entered,x=Room)) + 
  geom_point(color = 'darkred') + 
  add_rects() + 
  geom_point(color = 'darkred') + 
  scale_x_discrete(breaks=rooms_to_display) +
  theme_minimal() + 
  theme(axis.text.x = element_text(angle = 65, hjust =1)) + 
  ylab('percent of times room killed run') + 
  coord_cartesian(ylim = c(0,0.4)) + 
  xlab('Room')

So that work! I just have to create a function for my rooms. The only thing that is a little bit hackly is that I have to call add_rects() after geom_point() otherwise the range of the rect is incorrect, this results in rects being above the points the the coloring to be off. My current workaround for this problem is to then and another geom_point() call after add_rects() but thats a bit hack-y for my taste since youre ploting the points twice. I think to fix this would require a mapping between room number and room in in the add_rects() function but Im not sure if thats something I want to figure out right now.

make the all the dungeons blue for some reason this doesnt work

Ok lets dive a little deeper into the analysis

rooms_ordered$kill_frac <- rooms_ordered$times_killed_run / rooms_ordered$times_entered

In checking out this data frame Im particularly interested in room 4ON31, aside from the first overworld section 1OXXX, this is the largest run killer in the overworld. Im wondering if this run is the distinction between the double hundo route and the 30-30 route. My scraper only catches double hundo routes not 30-30.

explore_runs <- room_data %>%
  filter(Room == '4ON31' ) %>%
  filter(is.na(Duration) == TRUE)

I now have a list of run where I can manually check for 30-30, there are 21 candidate runs here, which honestly seems a bit low. But who knows. Im going to open up my videos and have a look.

Lets check out run 6301, which is in my file 01Dec2017-2. Ok so on this instance, he went out of order, but not exactly 30-30. Im going to check another, 6541, in 06Dec2017-2. Ok so Ive confirmed that these runs are where the double hundos split from the 30-30s. I could re-do these or filter these runs out, but I think ill just leave them in for the time being since they represent such a small fraction of the total runs (21/4581 or 0.5%).
